            <p>Philada.&#44; Pa.<lb/>
                Sep. 30. 1891.<lb/></p>
            <p>Dear Rabbi&#58;&#45;<lb/></p>
            <p>A year has gone by since<lb/> I wrote to you wishing you a happy<lb/> new year.  But&#44; as this old year is<lb/> gliding away and may it take all<lb/> curses along&#44; a new year is coming on<lb/> and soon we will crown it.<lb/></p>
            <p>The year that is now running away<lb/> shall be remembered by us.  It has wit&#45;<lb/>nessed acts of cruelty and persecution<lb/> only <sic>equalled</sic> once in our history.<lb/></p>
            <p>May the new year that is coming<lb/> upon us be a period of redemption for<lb/> our oppressed <sic>brethern</sic>&#44; and may<lb/> the Almighty grant you and your<lb/> family health according to your hearts&#39;<lb/></p>
                
                <pb n="2"/>
            <p>desire.  May He protect you from all<lb/> trouble because we read in the book of<lb/> Proverbs&#58;&#45; &#91;Hebrew&#93;<lb/> Respectfully<lb/> Your pupil&#44;<lb/> Gershon Levi.<lb/></p>
            </body>
    </text>
